comment: It takes two to tango. Nobody seems to understand that. They both played the game, until one quit, which I won't bother sharing my opinion about. The willpower they both have is the reason they both are so successful. Skills was only a result. That willpower at a world class level put in a relationship with someone with the same willpower ended up with them comparing themselves for the first time in their life. They started to realize some faults of their own. In other words they got a reality check when they met their ''match''. Notice how the female was the only one to admit to her pain. Even though it was too late, the fact that Amber risked her whole life just to be with him meant her love for Johnny was true, no matter what other people call her, she is braver than her ex partner. In Johnny's defense, there is over thousands of years of propaganda that a male can not admit to his pain and shedding a tear is equivalent to removing all hopes that someone will actually hug you and love you, and even if they do so one day you still got to keep up the mask as to not lose it. You can hear how she's fighting to get Johnny to admit to his pain as well while holding back all tears. She felt a betrayal. Even after their vows, she was in fact all alone in this world. I don't think she realized that it is not Johnny's fault, but how the portrayal of men and women in this world has ruined this marriage just like many others. Poor Johnny couldn't even cry in front of her when a loved one died, instead it all has to go out as anger. I have no doubt that generation Z will be the first stage of removing the portrayals of men and women as we know them today. I know we will succeed and I will start with myself. If you were wondering what I meant with she risked her whole life is the fact that pain and hurt will make all your career, friendship and family relations treat you like someone else for the rest of your life. You don't risk losing everyone, you risk losing yourself and that's why there is such a thing called professional help. Not because they know how to remove pain, there is no fucking cure. They just don't have a personal relationship to you, so your not risking your whole life to be able to tell someone <<Hey! i'm hurting right now and I just realized I am taking that out on other people. Can you listen to me enough in hopes that I will go back to being able to deal with my pain on my own again.>> A side note, even though everyone is so ashamed of pain, please remember that the humans in this world that have brought something beautiful for everyone to share is the people who have accepted that pain exists, and they want to bring something more to this world than that. For your information, I am a hypocrite so don't take my words as fact. Being honest with yourself is something some never learn, and some learn after they look death in the eye, or the death of someone you love. I have looked death in the eye and still can't stay true and stand tall. Even though there is a high probability of you being denied professional help like me, please give it a shot if you think it could be helpful. They have to say yes to a certain number of people I am guessing and I hope your one of them :) Anyhow, please just leave them be. No amount of willpower can remove pain from life. They are both humans just like you and me. Treat them accordingly and stop calling them names, and start focusing on what you were meant to do in this life. As will I, was just tired of all these mean comments :(

comment:
Aba, when you defined "gaslighting" I broke down crying man. I've seen the term used all over the internet but I guess I never looked into what it really meant. My ex I was with for 15 years did this to me all the time and I never had a word for it. She made me feel like shit and this realization hit me like a shitload of bricks.

Edit: Holy shit, I finished the video‚Äîthe recording gave me fucking flashbacks of every "argument" I sat through with my wife (basically her screaming at me, and whenever I'd try to defend myself verbally, she'd have none of that shit and her temper would just get worse). Word-for-word, it was always "YOU *NEVER* DO THIS. YOU *NEVER* DO THAT." It didn't make sense to me; it felt like I was being blamed for things I never thought or said. At a certain point I realized it was all her projecting on me and shortly after I started standing up for myself by pointing that out and aired _some_ of my grievances after listening to her yell and nag for _years,_ she hit me with the divorce. I realize now _I_ should have been the one to divorce _her_ long ago.

There's a saying I identified with during that time that I actually said to her face: "You can really dish it out, but you can't take it." It's so true of her, and it's kind of soured me to women at large. But I wonder how common that is amongst man-woman relationships. It was reassuring to hear that Preach and his wife don't yell and disrespect one another. Ideally, that's how I'd have it be too. I'm not into that shit; I just want to peacefully coexist, respect, and love one another. But for some women it seems like arguing is a blood sport or something.

comment: She did not go to the right preschool nor school in general! Cause I remember being a kid and being taught at a Special Needs track team, Church Preschool and grades up, and homeschooling to never ever put my hands on others. Even when I was just messing around not hurting anyone not hitting none of that. I was told not to put my hands on others even if they were okay with it. Unfortunately I had to relearn it as a teenager. I can admit when I messed up. I thought it was okay to lightly punch someone in the arm as a good job kinda thing. Like a high five because I saw all the teenage boys doing it. (There wasn't a lot of teenage girls at the time for me to learn from.) Doesn't matter what I thought or what behaviours I saw being acceptable. I should've never put my hands on anyone. Thankfully I was able to fall back on the info I was taught as a kid and I stopped doing it. I later learned that the Church Teen group I grew up in was considered far worse then actual schools and highschool to kids who went to highschool. I was homeschooled so I didn't really know how bad or good highschool could be. Talking to my cousin's and friends I knew, I found out that the schools in my area at least, are not safe or good schools. So I'm glad I never went. I'm still pretty social and I might not be able meet tons of people and make friends but when I do meet people they become lifelong friends of mine. So I considered that a plus to me at least. Also as much as people might say school's good for social skills, for learning, making friends, you're self esteem. Maybe in some cases but for the most part no. No it's not and if you say it is, you're either in a really nice expensive school, or you're straight up oblivious to those that are not having a good time! I know for a fact that school would've made my self esteem ten times worse then it already was, I would have not made a lot of friends because I had a lot of physical and neurological problems at a young age, and I would have been bullied a lot. I was not a very assertive kid when I was young. That's why even in my Church setting I was picked on a lot and excluded from a lot of things by my so called "Friends". I'm sorry to anyone who went to my Church when they were kids/teenagers because it was a pretty toxic place.

comment: It shouldn‚Äôt be hard to understand that taking accusations seriously (unless they are absolutely insane from the get go) and doing a thorough investigation is the best thing for everyone. If the person is actually guilty you want a strong, sound, case with evidence. If they have been falsely accused, you want that to be brought to light and hopefully charges brought against the false accuser (though this is rare, and I understand why because I know guys that have been falsely accused & they just want it to be over but they need to start pressing for charges). Doing a shoddy investigation that runs on predisposed belief in the ‚Äúvictim‚Äù (loaded language that works against the presumption of innocence and should not be tolerated) you‚Äôre not doing any favors for legit victims. Wrongfully convicting people does nothing to help anyone. It only harms.

comment:
Although this is not uptodate and so much more has come out, Johnny leading up to the divorce showed many signs of someone being at least emotionally/mentally abused.  When they were together in public I thought something not right here.  He doesn't seem happy and often the way he looked to her in public was a warning to me.  She looked in charge.  When the photos came out her expression everything looked like an act and I couldn't believe it.  Then when he was not even charged with a crime and the police saw no evidence I was relieved as it just did not fit in with my own observations.  Many got confused thinking the divorce settlement made him guilty.  It didn't.  The media convicted him that was all and I was  appalled how Hollywood treated him.  I won't be watching Radcliffe anymore after his comments.  He also convicted him without any evidence. 

¬†I always wanted Johnny to speak up and I thought when I saw her with metoo and l'oreal playing the victim how can he tolerate this.  I hoped the truth would come out and was amazed and pleased when Johnny finally laid it all out there.  I knew it would not be easy for him but sometimes one just has to stand up and be counted.  He knew all the dirty laundry would be out there and he is a pretty private person.  So it was so brave of him.  She has tried to ridicule him in so many ways but all she has done is shown herself to be what she is.  I have liked Johnny Depp as enjoyed his offbeat character but particularly because I saw how kind he was with his fans.  However now I have gained true respect for him.  Apart from trying to clear his name he is pivotal in highlighting male abuse victims which is very hidden.  Men Don't Tell is a film title of a male abuse victim which was a made for tv move in 1993.  I watched this a long time ago and it was really a big eye opener as to why men do not speak up.  So what Johnny is doing now is bigger than him it is highlighting male abuse suffering.  We need more films and documentaries about this subject to educate people that this is a common occurrence.  Then perhaps with that education people who have never suffered it will be educated as to how it can occur. 

¬†Johnny is owed alot of apologies by Hollywood but sadly I don't think he will get them.  At least individuals like Radcliffe who openly convicted him I hope they will do the right thing and publically apologise, we shall see.

¬† I am a woman and I believe in women's rights.  I am a woman and I also believe in men's rights.  That is true equality.

comment:
I spent 5 years with a guy like her. It was physical in the first 6mos. He had me feeling so bad and that I was the problem. After awhile, I stopped trying to resist and I would just take the yelling, take the hands, take the blame. I would leave after he was done freaking out and just walk and sit alone. Every fight would start because I had a different opinion and he would get mad I didn't agree with him. If I did agree, he would get mad and say things like, only mindless people don't have their own thoughts. I was so warped by this point in my life I felt worthless. It's hard to love someone and it's even harder to have to tell someone you love that they are hurtful, mean, and violent. In 5 years, I only told one person anything that Happened. I remember because it was the first time he punched me in the face. It was a breaking point. From names, choking till unconscious, hitting, forceful restraining, things got shitty. I only talk about it now if it can help some one else in a bad spot. When I broke up with him, he threatened to kill my dad (that he never met), my dog, and when I said no, he proceeded to yelling cuss and call me all sorts of names. Twas a real shit show.

Man or woman, if you can't conversate with your partner without getting mad, violent, or defensive, than YOU and your partner need help and support. And if your are being hurt by your partner it's okay to walk away. She is toxic. Instead of helping find solutions, she just hammers him with guilt.

comment:
This i exactly why i hate every protest for one thing, its so 1 sided and it doesn't matter what happens on the other side, because "Our problem is bigger, so what you have been through doesn't matter.". I don't believe in "black lives matter" it excludes all the other races that needs help too, i don't believe in "woman's rights" it doesn't account for the things woman do to men, what I believe in is "Every life matters" and "Anyone should have the same rights" unless they are a criminal of a certain degree. Im tired of this life where people are fighting for womens rights saying "we don't have any and we need them", but then turning around and using force against the "enemy" aka a person they identify as one, because they resemble the real criminal, or the people who use force and pretend it was for a good cause blah blah blah. This man who has put up with this woman was accused of something he didn't do, this man was accused for doing something that someone else had done to him, this man was manly enough and smart enough to know when to step out, this man is a victim, he is a man who was treated harshly by a woman and then by a society that only believes in black and white, as society that sees one side and decides that because they are a woman or black that the victim is them because they are "oppressed", when in reality its not black and white, its black, gray, white. They decide since he is a man that he is being a wimp for feeling bad for getting hit by a woman, but as they say that they are also saying this group of people who we are calling strong is weak, they are saying that just because she is a woman its impossible for her to hurt a man, they are contradicting their own beliefs and their own fighting stance. 
   Im not saying woman cant be abused, but im also not saying men cant either. Life is a grey zone and people really need to stop and think about what could be in the zone they call "black" aka the bad side. People need to sit down and think what if im wrong on this thing, what did i do wrong this time and try to defuse their own thinking, try to be on the other side of the line, even if it feels wrong. Hitler was a bad man, he was bad and we know that, but people still sympathies with him, why? They may be wrong, but have we ever stopped to ask why they think he was right? I know its an extreme comparison, but still. Hitler did what he did knowing he was wrong, but thinking he was right, he didn't stop to think about what is could be doing wrong because he knew he was wrong.
   Long story short people who are not willing to look at the other side of an argument, even when they are fighting for a noble cause, are the reason the world can never be equal, they are the reason innocent people are accused and perpetrated for wrongs they have not done. Men, women, Blacks, Asians, Hispanics, Whites, etc. are all equally an issue in society it doesn't matter what you are, what you look like, or where you are from, there is never just a black and white situation, its all gray, light gray, medium gray, dark gray, and many more grays. There is no complete white or black until there is evidence and if someone says "This person hurt me" don't completely discredit them nor completely give them all the credit, because a person is innocent until proven guilty, that stands for the accuser and the accused. 
   People need to understand nothing ever completely goes the way you want it too, so don't trust or distrust someone until you have the proof to, feelings are never enough, we need to approach things in life at the middle grounds until we fiscally cant anymore, thats when we make the decision on whether its wrong or right, but even after crossing the line keep your foot on it so you don't run into the void, have a rope to grab when you feel like you are sinking.

comment:
About ten years ago, I was engaged to a woman, and turns out, her ex husband was violent toward her. After we got engaged, and I moved in with her (and her girls 3 & 5), she developed PTSD. Scared the Hell out of me. She would go from 0-60 instantly, and could not be deescalated. (Screaming, yelling wild accusations, throwing things, etc.) I asked her mom to stay with us for a week, to help. We made a conscious decision to call the police if she ever got physical. 
She did, and I made the call, while grandma tried to comfort the girls, who were in terrified shock, and screaming as well, seeing their mother lose all control. I'm 6'5", 220 lbs at the time, and my fiance was 5'8", and maybe 105 lbs, very willowy, like a ballerina. When the cops came, they just looked at me, and put the burden on me as to what to do. (Having learned more about domestic violence, I'm surprised they didn't drag me away anyhow.) Physically, I was fine, but mentally/emotionally? Devastated. 
Nobody ever took it seriously, especially as I was literally more than twice her weight, and close to a foot taller.
It's real. More than most believe.

comment:
About the men's rights:

 Men are human beings with problems and they should have advocates. The issue is MEN aren't building shelters where men can feel safe after abuse. Men aren't advocating for self defence classes for the physical altercations like bullying and sexual assault. As a feminist, I believe in those causes and will FOR SURE show up in full support of these programs.

The issue is when men try and steal the hard-earned spotlight that women are using to FINALLY speak their minds and bring up their issues. And do I agree with everything said on that platform? No. And I will critique it right there and then. But the platform is important.

It's like how a lot of other races steal the spotlight from black rallies and discussions for their issues, when what they should be doing is making their own platforms that fight for their rights. NOT in retaliation of the effort of a race to empower themselves but in inspiration and solidarity of minorities that are not their own.

We've all been raised by a sick society and all have prejudices. Feel free to constructively critique the feminist movement. I do. But instead of trying to tear down this movement (that is still a matter of life and death in non-priveleged countries and areas) make your own movement, carve out your own time and dispel the myths about what it means to be a men's right advocate.

I will be ready to volunteer at any shelters/ fundraisers that promote the equality and responsible freedom of all genders and sexes. Just holla.

comment: My husband and I dont fight. We disagree. If we get to "about to fight" area you can feel the tension, he leaves. As in, goes to another room to be left alone, goes to the store etc. away for an hour or less. Enough time for him to gather his thoughts and calm down. This way when we come back together to talk he is calm and receptive. The first few times he did this I was angry. But he explained it. He said, "you are my wife. The most important thing to me. And I would rather gather my thoughts and listen, explain, and if need be apologize, then get mad and say things I don't mean or will completely regret. I know that words cant be taken back. They hurt, and I would never want to do that to you." After that, I gave him his space. Never had a problem. I wish more people would handle things that way. It saves a lot of trouble.

comment:
Living in Australia and working in fast food when I was younger I witnessed multiple instances of women abusing their men in public with no recourse. There's one instance that comes to mind which I think I'll remember forever. I was 18/19 working for red rooster in Midland. There was this lower income family that would always be at the shops. They'd frequently get food from my work when I was on because we'd chat and share some small talk. They had 3 young boys who were relatively well mannered for the area. As time went on I would see the couple having more and more agressive arguments in public. One day it became so bad that the man was clearly retreating into the shops and protecting the children as the woman was screaming and swearing all kinds of obscenities at the man. She was throwing everything and anything that she could get her hands on at the guy and even started hitting him. He was pleading for her to not do this in front of her kids and she called him a coward and all manner of things and slapped him across his head. Security comes in to see what the situation is, first checks on the woman who's still animated then goes to the man to get his side to which he was brushing it all off as just another day in the office. Police were involved, it looked traumatic for the kids. The whole situation was terrible. I felt awful for not acting then myself. But what the hell do you do when there's kids involved and everything. 

Needless to say the following day they're walking through the shops again, the lady all bubbly as if nothing happened, the man with a few facial bruises looking defeated. Kids were with them and everything. I just don't understand where the justice is in this story for the man and their kids.

Sorry for the long story but even then years later I still think about that day and how I could've acted differently.

comment:
You mention that thing; "it requires patience". I've never been in an abusive relationship myself - after all, it most often does take a woman to start it and since I don't, violence doesn't happen with normal men. (And it's easy enough to spot a will-be male abuser to avoid the hell out of them. The fact Amber chose Johnny is because he's powerful (manipulatable), gentle and safe, someone easy to beat up.) 

When the news broke, I KNEW that whatever happened was because Amber was provoking it. It took me months to believe that he NEVER hit her back, because I'm only a girl, and don't have that patience. I wouldn't have judged him either, it was CLEAR she had that personality, that "want to think I'm a freaking femme fatale and this is my interpretation of it. So hot it hurts!" (Crazy-hot ratio men talk about... A bit too far on the crazy end.)

In that "abuse video" on TMZ, he never so much as calls her a bitch in a situation where an abusive man would have decked her already. I used to run a support group for victims of narcissistic abuse (Amber being a text bookcase) and NOT ONE of those women would have gone into that situation, with her husband already agitated about something, with a poorly hidden camera asking him how much wine he has had to drink, I mean... Talk about begging for it. She's HOPING to provoke him to hit her while the camera is rolling. Fails. She isn't scared. SHE is not scared of ANYTHING. Not being yelled at, being slapped, hit, punched... Nothing. 

The women I know wouldn't go on a dating site 10 years later with their face in the photo, in the fear of their ex. Despite claiming "Johnny is so jealous," this woman daunts him in the media, gets seen with big burly men just to show off how frail and fragile she is. (She even wears shoes at least 2-3 sizes too big for her in one series of photos, probably to give that fragile little girl in mommy's shoes vibe.) https://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3656670/Amber-Heard-looks-worryingly-jets-Los-Angeles-ex-Johnny-Depp-lays-low-private-island-Bahamas.html

Where was I going with this... The patience. HOW MUCH PATIENCE does it take for someone to NOT REACT? He is SUPERHUMAN... But then, a lot of guys have had to become superhuman just to be good enough... Now, #meToo is demanding mind-reading skills, too which... Another topic, but when even the female accuser cannot recall ever saying "no", then we've got a freaking problem. I can't remember having said "yes, honey, I wish to engage in sexual activity with you" to a guy, the consent is implied in "I'm NOT FIGHTING YOU, nor am I SAYING no", never do I sign any effin' papers, am I, but now, these ALREADY THEN grown women go: "oh he should have known there was nothing consensual about it!" So many of these women's OWN ACCOUNT doesn't even IMPLY non-consensual behavior. First, you read these stories like OMG poor thing, then you go back and go... WHERE was the clue he was supposed to pick up on? "But if you say no, it'll make them angry and then they rape you VIOLENTLY. Better let them rape you gently..." Fuuuuuk

The patience. It's SO DIFFICULT TO BELIEVE anyone could just stand there listening to this woman yap on about what "you did Johnny", and not go: "Wait, what?! What do you mean 'strong evidence'... The strongest DV case they've EVER seen?!" when you know this woman is delusional. But by now, he's probably heard it all, and he's just listening like "WHAAAT?!" (In the next audio that comes from after this one, you know.) We're still wrapping our minds around it, but he's like... OK. Same ol' same ol'. 

But the moment when it hits him in the next audio... "You're just a made-up thing in my head." That is beauty. That was gold. HE KNEW what so many people saw straight away. comment:
Thirty-three years ago, I met Johnny Depp just before he became famous, in a club on the Sunset Strip.  He walked up and started hitting on me. He was 23 years old, a peach-fuzzed baby, as cute as can be and genuinely friendly and sweet as sugar pie.  He cut right to the chase. "Hi, I'm Johnny Depp," he said, putting out his hand.  "I know who you are, " I said, shaking it.  "You DO?" he exclaimed in surprise. "Yeah, I work for a news service and I watch six hours of CNN programming a day," I said.  "It'm actually a writer, it's just my college job.  I saw you in a Showbiz Today segment about "21 Jump Street."  


"Wow, I just filmed that yesterday," he murmured. eyes sparkling, still holding my hand. His smile always meets his eyes and it never leaves. "You are so gorgeous and smart, too. I love that.  Will you go out with me?"


"No," I said, smiling.


YES, THIS UNBELIEVABLE FOOL SAID "NO" TO JOHNNY DEPP.


I was dating Blackie Lawless from W.A.S.P.  I was a worldly woman of 26 years, I thought.


(YES, I STILL KICK MYSELF, HARD, AND OFTEN.)


Johnny wasn't going to give up without a fight, however.


"Pleeeaaassseee???"  he begged in a sing-song voice, squeezing my hand, "Oh, pretty please? You're so pretty.  You're just my type!"  


YES, IT IS I, DUMBASS OF THE CENTURY; SHE WHO SAID "NO" TO JOHNNY DEPP, NOT ONCE, BUT TWICE.  


I smiled and shook my head no.  I thought he was too young.  


"I'm going to be a big star!" he exclaimed softly, wistfully, as if still realizing that all of his dreams were about to come true.


"I know, " I said, and stood there holding his hand like a colossal dumbass, still saying no.


Oh, why, Why, WHYWHYWHY didn't I leave that club that night with Johnny Depp and never look back??????


I went on with my life and hooked up with several men who treated me like Amber treats Johnny.


JOHNNY, COME BACK, i'M SORRY I WAS SO DUMB, I WOULD LOVE ANOTHER CHANCE TO TREAT YOU LIKE THE KING OF MY HEART!!!!  I DON'T CARE IF EVERYONE THINKS YOU ARE A WOMANBEATER AND NO ONE WILL HIRE YOU, I KNOW WHAT THE TRUTH IS!!!


~*!:.S.I.G.H.:!*~  The one who got away. 


oK, GUYS, LISTEN UP: if a woman puts her hands on you violently or even hints at it, don't argue, don't put up a fight, just get away from her asap, FAST AND FOREVER. NO MORE CONTACT. This is a pivotal moment. A big test. She is showing you what she is capable of, a hint of what she has planned for you, she is showing you the way it's going to be.   You have to be very careful how you walk away from this kind of person. You can't just hustle her out the door and tell her it's over. You already know what will happen if you put your hands on her in any way, even if you have just cause to send her packing, and it might happen even if you don't put her hands on her.  You have to get her calmed down and make her think everything is okay, then leave her place, or get her to leave your place and make her think it's her idea. Because the first time she puts her hands on you, it's a test to see how much she can control you, get you under her thumb, and it will just get worse from that moment on. 


If at this point you are reading my comment and thinking, "yeah, she's crazy, but the sex is so great," then quit reading, we are done here, because you might be a grown man, but you are emotionally immature, there's no talking to you when you're walking around with your dick in your hand, and you will have to learn the hard way. If you are thinking, "how do I get myself out of this mess as seamlessly as possible," then continue reading.  


As I said, it's really important to pretend to do what she is trying to manipulate you into doing: living to please and serve her. Do what you have to do, say what you have to say, to make her believe you are dismayed at having angered her, you're sorry, it won't happen again, kiss up to her, whatever, even if it makes you want to blow chunks, you are just trying to part on good terms so she doesn't implement Plan B: the Revenge of the Scorned Narcissist while she still has access to your physical presence. Which is basically what Amber is doing to Johnny right now. She even mentioned "Plan B" in a text to her father, right after she sent the text saying "FUCK YOU, DAD!"  Such a lovely, sweet, delicate flower you raised, there. Dad...


Once you get her to leave or you make your escape, you go FULL NO CONTACT, and also do all of the following, especially if she has ever been left unattended in your home or around your wallet for longer than five minutes:  Whether or not she lives with you, change the locks, install hidden security motion detection cameras that record 24/7,  change your passwords, close and re-open your bank accounts, consider re-keying your car locks and security fobs, etc.  As soon as she suspects that you have dared to defy her plan for your life of servitude and supply to her, she will straight set you up, put you in jail, keep your home, your car, your bank account, your kids, your dog, and move another guy in. Because, because.   Good luck getting a place to live and good job when you get out.  You will probably go back in.  And repeat. For life, until you die.  Don't feel special, she has probably done this to other guys.


It's not necessarily your fault you hooked up with a narcissistic sociopath. They know how fucked up they are, but instead of fixing it, they'll resort to extreme measures to get people to accept it, and their victims don't always see what's happening right away because they don't have experience with this level of fuckity-fucked-upness. It is seriously mind-warping how totally perfectly wonderful they can be, your dream come true for weeks, months, not a cloud in the sky, and then this happens.


I know, because it happened to me, three times in a row.  No matter how careful I was to watch for the "signs."  I almost lost everything to these worthless blobs of flesh, including my life. I escaped with everything intact, including my place to live, my vehicles, my cats, my excellent career and all of my teeth. I know I'm lucky.


And I get to tell people that Johnny Depp begged me to go out with him.  It's one of my favorite memories. I'm blessed.

comment: Man, poor guy, Lived through that myself for a couple of years. Borderline personality disorder is bad news, and that sure sounds similar. Yes, have pity for people with the condition, but stay well clear! Parallels what I went through so closely. I left at the point in the fights where things got nasty. Many nights hunkered down in a locked bathroom. Wineglasses smashed into my face, coming at me with knives, threatening suicide because I wouldn't come out for more abuse, in fact screaming bloody murder at 3 am to get the neighbors to call the police because I wouldn't come out of there for more craziness, and this is in a foreign country that I moved to out of love, where I hardly knew anyone and ended up isolated from my family because of this stuff.  It's been almost 2 years since I left and this stuff still makes me feel sick even hearing it happen to someone else. Still trying to get my head together before even thinking about another relationship. Just shows, money or status, it can happen to anyone, and it sucks bad. Takes a while to get your head screwed on straight afterward. I have nothing but the utmost sympathy for this guy.

comment: I 100% agree and would never want my son to be regarded that way, and I agree that people should not just believe anyone without critically thinking about the information presented. What is the appropriate way to address the problem of women not being believed when we report abuse, though? Maybe it could be addressed from the angle of just that people need to stop gaslighting everyone, regardless. I've been seriously harmed before by someone, and when I told the people necessary to prevent harm from being done to others, I was called a liar without any investigation or consideration. Even when you're trying to get protection from authorities for a child who's being physically abused, mothers often get treated like we're making it up just to get revenge on our ex, especially if the ex has a lot of money, and it really doesn't seem to matter if they obtained that money through selling lots of drugs - courts do not care. They only like to jail poor drug dealers, it seems. Rich ones can buy their way out of anything. This is a major problem though. The Marin Center for Judicial Excellence is one organization working to combat this, but it's an uphill battle because currently judges cannot be held accountable for the decisions they make in court, no matter what the outcome. So, I 100% agree that women shouldn't be believed just for the fact that they are a woman, because I definitely know there are cases where some women use that as a weapon for revenge. I've seen girls do really petty things to my adult son before, even making him lose his job due to their actions, etc., and I can totally see how easy it would have been for them to try and weaponize this idea against him. He's a really good person too with such a natural sense of morale; it would be farfetched for anyone to say anything about him, but I can still see how it could happen in the context of everyone just wanting to "believe her" no matter what. I'm just posing the question of how to appropriately deal with the root problem of where that idea came from in the first place, which is how often true accounts get dismissed, other than the "believe her" method that does have some serious problems as you all so very well point out here.

comment:
My ex-fiance said all that shit to me when she was putting her hands on me.  And I remember I used to think that women can't damage men too.  Then I quickly learned how wrongheaded that was when she put her hands on me for the last time.  Whiplash, a concussion, and a dislocated shoulder later, she, barehanded, had forced me to defend myself.  I broke up with her that night, told her she had to leave in the morning, and I never saw her again.  I also told her mother what happened and showed her my wounds when explaining the bruises on her arms from me grabbing her and pinning her to the door.  That's a woman I grew up with, who I'm 7 inches taller than and had 60 pounds on.

Guess what her mother told me.  She told me I should have knocked her daughter out.  She told me I'm her son, whether I marry her daughter or not because she helped raise me and *no one* has the right to put their hands on me.  She never taught me to be a doormat or punching bag.  She saw the damage to me and almost cried because she couldn't believe the condition I was in.  She was shocked that her daughter could do that to someone.  And she was outraged by the fact that men aren't allowed to defend themselves from legitimate threats on the grounds of gender.  I could have been killed if my ex wasn't too afraid of being hit back to stop when I reacted.

It won't get better without real help and the abused shouldn't have to sit through that process.  It was at that point that my stance changed.  If a woman knocks me on my ass, I'm going to knock her on hers and leave.  Fuck that shit.  Chivalry is stupid, irresponsible, and dangerous, and it's a good thing it's dying.  I will never let a woman hit me for free again.  I will never let a woman chase me out of my home again.  I will never let a woman take from me again.  I won't be bullied by women again.  Women are equally capable of being bullies.  Fuck bullies.  I hate bullies.  But if she's not like that, then I'll be the best man I can be for her - as long as she's the best woman she can be for me.

comment: I like the energy, but I want to put my two cents in because you may be spreading some misinformation. The fact of the matter is that if we want domestic violence to stop, we must as a society find ways to help those that abuse their partners and family learn how to stop. BUT this was an important revelation! She's a child, not in the "protect her innocence" sort of way, but the emotionally immature/volatile kind of way. I'm sad that a man at his age and level of success may have some self worth issues if this behavior was in any way acceptable... It's so gross she let people believe he was ALWAYS the aggressor(hell, or even the MAIN physical aggressor). Nothing's changed in the fact that we don't know all of what happened between them, but she's using classic abuser deflection language. If it was something that happened in the heat of the moment once, maybe twice, but you felt remorse and like that wasn't how you wanted to be, you would hold yourself accountable and not make it about what the other person did(unless it was self defense and clearly it was not). We can all understand being pushed to the limit, but it's a CHOICE to use violence over and over again as a way of handling conflict. I hope she's publicly held to task, or it's all bullshit!
